node.text:
In 1990, an improperly installed window on British Airways Flight 5390 fell off during mid-flight causing rapid decompression in the cockpit.

Flight attendant Nigel Ogden just happened to be entering the cockpit when he heard the loud bang and saw the pilot getting sucked out. In the reenactment image, you can see Ogden holding on to his legs, while the co-pilot is trying to rapidly descend in order to reach a safer altitude.

As the co-pilot attempted to contact air traffic control to make an emergency landing, Ogden was starting to develop frostbite from the severe cold. Most of the crew thought the pilot was already dead, but Ogden continued to hold on. There was also the fear that if he did let go, the body might collide with the plane's engine, wing or stabilizer, creating more havoc. All he knew for sure was that the pilot was slipping further and further out the window and his head was repeatedly slamming against the fuselage.

After 15 minutes of flying with a broken window, the plane landed safely at Southampton Airport. Ogden suffered frostbite on his face and damaged one of his eyes; he also dislocated his shoulder. The pilot miraculously survived with frostbite and multiple fractures on his arms and hands.

An investigation later revealed that the window that had been newly installed just 27 hours before the flight had used incorrect bolt sizes. Of the 90 bolts that were used, 84 of them were 0.026 inches (0.66 mm) too small in diameter. The other 6 bolts had the correct diameter, but were short by 0.1 inches (2.5 mm). The bolts were supposed to be 0.8 inches, not 0.7 inches‼️✈️

node.text:
Recent incident with the F-16B fighter of the Taiwan Air Force was caught on video
At the Taiwan Air Force Pingdong Air Base, an F-16B fighter failed to stop after landing and flew off the runway, burying its nose in the ground.
The incident occurred during the preparation for the 37th Hanguang exercise, which is scheduled to begin in September.
The official representative of the Taiwanese Air Force said that the cause of the incident with the F-16B fighter (b/n 6829), assigned to the Hualien Air Base, was a "mechanical malfunction". He noted that the pilot was not injured in the incident, and the fighter received minor damage‼️✈️ 🎥: @heatshellsaviation
